text: The MonsterVerse is an American media franchise and shared fictional universe that is centered on a series of monster films featuring Godzilla and King Kong, produced by Legendary Entertainment and co-produced and distributed by Warner Bros. The first installment was Godzilla (2014), a reboot of the Godzilla franchise, which was followed by Kong: Skull Island (2017), a reboot of the King Kong franchise. The next film to be released will be Godzilla: King of the Monsters (2019), followed by Godzilla vs. Kong (2020). With two films released to date, the series has grossed over $1 billion worldwide.

text: The story so far: The Earth is on the brink of the endtimes from humanity's stupidity and the titans (kaiju) have woken up to fix it. They all have different plans for how best to protect Earth. They will go on an all out battle royale to decide who reigns supreme, but Godzilla is strangely absent. At first humanity puts trust in Mothra, who seems to be most empathetic to us. Rodan is pretty bad, turning an entire city to ash, but Ghidorah may be even worse as a tyrant. He is kicking everybody's ass. The military is forced to wake up Godzilla to dethrone Ghidorah. Humanity prefers to Godzilla's rule to Ghidorah's. All I can saw is, you're damn right in Godzilla we trust! Godzilla seems to be losing, but the military intervenes for him, letting him win a close victory.

text: When I was a kid back in the 70s, on Saturday mornings after cartoons, a local channel would run a Godzilla/Kaiju movie!! I was obsessed with the King Of The Monsters (I brought my Godzilla/Shogun Warrior toy to school for show and tell one day!). If I was bad during the week, my parents would tell me, if I didn't behave I wouldn't be allowed to watch that weeks Godzilla movie, so you better believe I straightened up my act. My favorite movie for a long time was Destroy All Monsters, but I now believe everything has been building up TO THIS MOMENT!! I can not wait to see this movie. It's like a culmination of 50 years of being a Godzilla fan and it is so close!! :D

text: Wow, this is LEAPS AND BOUNDS BETTER than the first one that came out a few years ago. I just hope the STORY (the writing) is just as good as the amazing visuals.  Having Bryan Cranston in the first Godzilla DIDN'T make it a good film, although every scene he was in he stole by far. I was so surprised they only kept him in the film for  20 mins or so. After that, the film fell off with the inferior writing and cast. The only other great actor in the first film , and he's back in this film as well is Ken Watanabe.  Also in this film is the great Zhang Ziyi, which I think many viewers either are not familiar  with her or don't realize or recognize that she is in the film (see 0:55) She was in Memoirs Of A Geisha and the CLASSIC FILM Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon along  with LEGENDARY martial artist/ actress Michelle Yeoh and  Chow Yun-Fat.  This looks incredible and they have revealed more fight scenes and monsters. I think Anguirus is in this as well  (@ 0:15)  To hear them say in the clip, 'How many of these things are there!?? (@ 0:15) and the answer be SEVENTEEN means that hopefully there will be some other classic monsters from the Godzilla films to show up in this. Although, having TOO MANY and not be able to expand or give more background on them would only be a waste. Especially if those monsters are killed off in this film.  Overall, I am hopeful and really amped for the release of this film in May. The only downer connected to this clip will be all the FAKE 'REACTIONS' from the multitude of SHEEPLE  looking to post their fake reactions to this when most of them are only posting reaction videos because others are and they want to be included in the Reaction Mashup clips but they have NO CLUE who most of these monsters are, their back story or the history of the Godzilla franchise, and as a man that has grown up with these films since way back in the 70's, I can spot a FUGAZI a mile away. -lol   'REACTION BOTS' BEWARE, I will be posting some shit on your clips if you are one of the fugazi's I am talking about.

text: OK, afan theory here of the premise of the movie, unless the trailers have been intentionally misleading, which is always possible.Â  ThisÂ trailer clearly states that the other Titians are "in a pack, responding directly to an Alpha".Â  They have also stated in trailers,Â "which of these Titians are here to protect us, which are here to destroy us."Â   WHAT IF - There are Two Kings/Alphas(Godzilla and Ghidorah), and the rest of the Titians pick the Alpha they wish to rule?Â  It also seems clear that Godzilla either has a temporary setback from his first round with Ghidorah, or has still not fully recuperated from battling the Mutos.Â  This means that we could see a huge team up of Titians on either side and we may get some (hopefully Rodan) that may start out working with Ghidorah, that when a rejuvenated Godzilla (who probably gets a nuclear boost from the humans) returns, switch sides to turn the tide of the battle.Â  Mille Bobby Brown's character also will play some role in this battle of the Titians,Â  as they may be attracted to her, and/or she can communicate with them.

text: This is  probably unrealistic to ask, but can you please remove the unnecessary dialogue such as, "My God.." "..zilla."      Please get rid of the unnecessary dialogue in this film, or at least most of it.  By unnecessary I am referring to the lines that interrupt the intensity, the flow of suspense or action or important information, the immersion of the moment, just to show someone saying, "That's messed up," or, "It's Godzilla's world, we just live in it."  I've put a lot of thought into this, so if you or anyone reads this, I appreciate it very much.  Not all will agree but here's some thoughts from a Godzilla fan, a movie fan and what I'd like to see as far as films being made heading toward the future with film making/storytelling (starting with my love of Godzilla and all the themes and concepts and possibilities he and his friends and enemies, including us, stand for).  Despite the heartfelt intro here, it's a simple request to consider that I think could strengthen instead of harm; the deep, spiritual, important and impactful tales that Godzilla films and concepts have stood for, promote and have made us think about since 1954.  Thanks!    Godzilla films and us true Godzilla fans have the unique chance to pave the way for thought providing, heavy concept and deeply emotional and inspiring stories with impactful messages, without the need for useless, gimmicky dialogue.  Let Godzilla and his true fans trample over the countless of other movies who rely on that same cheesy dialogue every other line, every single scene, and show them this is how you make a movie!  Let them realize they're just spec of failing dust.    Would be cool if Godzilla broke, no, shattered the mold and paves over the unfortunate trend of fleeting, forgettable hollywood movies.  Instead of writers injecting unnecessary and cringey dialogue into our beloved and potentially poignant films, our Godzilla and his films can set the standard for well crafted films containing deep emotion, heavy concepts, introducing new ways of thinking about our planet and our role and place on it and of course, unworthy to behold, ancestral battles - for us to survive on it.    Godzilla is too important, culturally, in real life and in the stories that he and his allies and enemies can weave to have this kind of dialogue anywhere near.  Godzilla franchise stands for too much to not be taken seriously.  He represents and demonstrates nature, ancient awesomeness, balance, protection, defense and the ability (our ability) to protect or harm our one and only true home - as well as our one and only true family - each other.  Us true fans don't need all these hollywood written jokes every other line of dialogue.  These films have a unique responsibility and chance to tell epic tales at least a bit more seriously than some of the the other slapstick ridden franchise with over the top nothingness.  Godzilla and it's heavy concepts, themes and lessons can actually contribute to the world, and to the world of cinema, through thought provoking and deeply emotional storytelling, through profound messages and inspiration.  The world of Godzilla offers genuine reflection about us and our role in the world and our place on our actual planet.  Get these awful attempts at humor out of our movie.  A few lines, max.  The rest needs to be focused, to be memorable and to go down in history.    Godzilla and his friends and enemies and us humans/animals who share the same planet and occupy the same space (on wildly differing scales), offer an exciting and unique world of giant creatures, good, bad and somewhere in between.  How we all survive among one another while we exist and operate at two dimensions of size/scale, the enormous and and tiny - and how we support or affect one another - while trying to survive and defend our planet and ultimately life = new and amazing concept for many to explore.  Imagine an age where these creatures suddenly did wake up and we did actually have to accept that they are a part of our planet and everyday existence - what an exciting thought and awesome concept!  The lore and ancient awesomeness of these guys and their relation to our planet and everything on it is wonderful and allows for deep and meaningful storytelling.   a bit more..

No more bloody sequels, prequels, or remakes. No more splitting books into multiple movies just for extra money. Maybe those days are over. Nobody wants movies with good character development and plot substance anymore. It's like people can't handle it. They need dumbed down entertainment. That's all that this is. Sure, it looks great. text: I don't care what anyone says, to me, this will be the best movie of 2019 and possibly the best Godzilla movie of all-time. It's got a cast of really good actors and actresses. The CGI looks fantastic. Godzilla, Mothra, Rodan, and King Ghidorah look absolutely stunning and once again, that music is just beautiful and it almost made me shut a tear. Godzilla will always be my all-time favorite monster. Godzilla 2014 was good, but this movie, however is so gonna blow 2014 out of the water.

text: Godzilla: The True King of Monsters  Rodan: The Fire-Sky King  Mothra: The Sky Queen  Ghidorah: The Golden False King  A Godzilla fan since the age of 3 and I NEVER thought I see the day where he's truly feeling like what I saw him as: THE king of ALL monster. He's the biggest he's ever been, commands presence, feels unstoppable. It brought me to tears to have seen Godzilla grow as big as he is (both popularity and physically) as I grew too, but to see him as force of nature that helps all despite his destructive power, as well as getting my defining Godzilla movie. I've seen them all, most of them before I was born and teased for getting excited at seeing what was 'new' to me. Now, it's new but brings back the big 4 of monsters like the old days. It's my Godzilla movie and goddamn am I happy to have it. Long live the King.

text: The previous trailers looked okay in terms of CG and the Clair de Lune soundtrack plus certain select shots helped breathe some life into the Godzilla movie franchise. However, the new scenes shown in this trailer have horrendous CG especially in the opening shot, which is drawn out and invites a lot of scrutiny compared to the rest of the trailer. The second scene of Mothra looks fine and we've seen it before as well as other 'epic shots', but it's only a few seconds. The third scene is where I feel offended even though I'm not a hardcore Godzilla fan (my apologies). It's certainly difficult to create a realistic 'mountain-like kaiju erupting out of a mountain' scene, but the particle effects in this look like it's from a decade ago from maybe a lower-budget movie. I was about to blame Youtube compression for the muddy image quality, but it's unfortunately not the case.  My main skepticism besides the CG (I have a lot of gripes besides the points above) is the story from all the past trailers combined. It looks like a generic 'American scientists plus military discover mankind-threatening monsters and some Japanese ppl conveniently inform them of their folklore/legends to make the kaiju larger than life' story. I didn't see this being a successful blockbuster then and I certainly don't see it now after watching this last trailer. Guesstimate: 55/100 or along the lines of Battle Angel: Alita and other similarly mediocre CG adaptations out nowadays.

text: **NO SPOILERS **  If you saw 2014' Godzilla & thought this was gonna be like tht one you are wrong. This movie was so kool in a lot of diff ways & will connect generational interpretations w/ new & die-hard lifelong fans as I am. From the mythos of the Titans & special appearances to the connections 2 some very real environmental issues revolving in our world regarding human carelessness w/ pollution, war & nuclear waste. All derivatives of the original concept of the Godzilla character & creation in 1954 as a metaphor to Hiroshima & Nagasaki 11 yrs before. There are of course great hat-tips thru-out the movie to industry greats such as original producer & creator of the original franchise Tomoyuki Tanaka & famed japanese actor & "rubber-suit" actor Haruo Nakajima who passed in '17. There's even a small tip to Ray Harryhausen, the godfather of American stop-motion monsters back then as well as a awesome soundtrack giving props to the original 1950's score. So much in this movie tht was expected by fans & I think it delivers on all fronts. There were some definite MEH spots here & there (brad whitfords character for example) & the really bad cover of B.O.C.'s Godzilla @ the end but this movie & the way it honors & brings new life into the Toho characters & storylines I've been in awe of all My life will have TRUE fans of the every Gojira franchise seeing this a couple times @ least.  LONG LIVE THE KING!!

text: THIS IS A MUST READ COMMENT!!!!!!  First off, let me just say that this was my most anticipated movie of 2019. Second, Godzilla: King of The Monsters was absolutely INSANE!!!!!!!!!! What a masterpiece Mike Dougherty has made!! This was a once in a lifetime movie experience that I will always remember for the rest of my life. I am SO glad I saw this in IMAX. I will never forget how massive the battle sequences were, and the monsters were just GODLIKE on the screen. Everything about this movie was pure perfection. This is why Legendary Entertainment is my favorite movie studio. Their movies almost NEVER disappoint. I could not believe what I was seeing on screen. My jaw was on the floor. This is without a doubt, one of the best if not THE best monster movie/creature feature ever made in cinema history. I will be getting this on Blu-ray when it comes out. I recommend this movie to ANYONE who loves monster movies and action films. This was the best movie I have seen this year so far.

text: While i knew any Godzilla movie will never compete against the likes of any Marvel Movie, and it wasn't surprising Kong Skull island would do better in the U.S because Kong is an American franchise, so the name would be bigger for the U.S audience. I still hoped it would reach at least 50 million on its first day. I'm devastated that it is barely scraping  97.8 million since thursday premiere and influenced by critics/rotten tomatoes.     Growing up as a Godzilla fan, I want the monsterverse to continue but if Godzilla King of the Monsters doesnt hit the box office over 200 million, goodbye any more Godzilla monsterverse after Godzilla vs Kong. ðŸ˜¢

text: spoiler alert for the man (Bradley Whitford) at 1:02 who finishes "...zilla..."     After watching this film, you would either really don't like him for his constant one-liners or you find him funny with his constant one-liners in nearly every scene. Honest I think the movie would be a just slightly tad better if they didn't try to make him and the other Monarch scientist/agent (Thomas Middleditch) as the film's "funny" characters. Maybe it's a nice throw back to the showa/Heisei cheesy human characters, but this one didn't score with me.   I liked the movie, mainly because I ALWAYS knew that the monsters and monster fights will be the absolute highlight of the Godzilla franchise and the humans to be either less than interesting or somewhat decent. But ironically, while the Monsterverse Godzilla love to talk about "balance," they couldnt find the perfect balance between the Kaijus/Monsters/"Titans" and human characters.

text: I don't know what the critics want out of this film after their reviews on Godzilla 2014.   Yes the human storyline was cheesy. The motivations were silly and some you just had to bear with. Having said that, I really LOVED and was AWED to experience the Titan fights from their human perspectives.  You'd feel as if you're on the plane, on the ground, scared for your own life and in submission to the behemoths as they destroyed the entire city without regard to our human sentiments and business.  The Titans were beyond EPIC. Their designs commanded fear and worship. The sounds they made--fron the weight of their bodies to their establishing roars-- would have you praying between your teeth.   This was a movie that listened to its fans and was created by people whom you couldn't deny to have genuine love for the character.  The fights were also some of the most beautiful visuals I have ever seen. The final battle between Gojira and Ghidorah delivered an epicness unparalleled. Rodan, upon his reveal, revelled (until of course when Ghidorah showed himself the bigger king of the skies). I could feel survival juice up the soldiers as he chased them through the clouds.  Let's talk about Mothra.   Mothra's design was revamped with aesthetics fit only for the queen of the heavens. Her fully spanning her wings for the first time was magical and evoked emotions and faith to her benevolence. That's why, Mothra's battle against Rodan made me and my boyfriend emotional. In fact, I got emotional every time Mothra got screentime. You just knew her destiny by the end of this.  Suffice it to say that this is a movie worth your money and time. What you're going to experience is not only a visual fiction, but also some of the passionate and most beautiful hard work of the film crew behind this.

text: I have never written a review before, as honestly I find them to be useless, and this movie has driven that point home for me. I absolutely refuse to remain silent on a movie franchise that I've cared about since I was a child, with a modern film that does its predecessors justice by breathing new life into an ancient movie franchise, get torn to shreds by enigmatic critics that look for the most minute details to mark as "cinematic sins".  Rotten Tomatoes has given Godzilla: King of the Monsters a 39%, with Metacritic backing them up with equally dreadful reviews, while a quick google search shows that most movie goers (literally ~90% of the people who saw this movie) actually enjoyed this film. I sometimes use reviews to gauge if I might enjoy a movie, or if it's even worth going to watch it, but I went into this movie completely blind; avoiding trailers and reviews like the plague because I knew I was going to see this film regardless, and I might as well keep as much of it as a surprise for myself. The reviews on Rotten Tomatoes complain about the most outlandish details, many of them critiquing the CGI in the film that was actually gloriously executed. I saw all my favorite monsters brought to life in new, horrifying detail that satisfied the long-term monster movie fanboy in me. I now realize the critics just see movies and rate them as their entire career, so firstly, should I care about the opinion of a person that could only land a job as someone who slashes movies to ribbons? They're only payed to critique movies, so of course they're going to analyze every little detail to the point where it's just tiresome and counter-intuitive. Also, it's easy, and not at all uncommon, for say . . a movie production company to shell out a couple extra bucks to critics to give certain films bad reviews, or their own films good reviews just so they can make more money. After seeing The Last Jedi get a 90% on Rotten Tomatoes, I was convinced either they're getting payed off to act as "influencers", or they do not represent the everyday movie-goer's best interests. Either way, I have no respect for their "critics" and have long since replaced their judgment with my own. That site is clearly dominated by Disney/Marvel fanboys that see anything else as a threat to their darling angel known as MCU. Seriously, a RT review referred to Legendary's project as "an MCUmonsterverse". With that said, King of the Monsters was an absolutely illustrious movie that attacked the weaknesses of Godzilla 2014. Godzilla and his gang get more screen time in this film, and more importantly Michael Dougherty found the right balance of monster battle and human interactions that deliver a simple plot giving enough reason as to why we have giant monster fights. Yes, some of the characters were a bit underwhelming, but the movie at least gave the main characters enough of a chance to establish their disposition, so that you won't agree with every character's respective actions, but you at least understand why those characters made those choices. Another point to address is that the movie uses the trope of "Humanity is killing the planet, and you should feel bad". It doesn't bring anything new to the storytelling table, but it definitely doesn't deserve any demerits either. The fact remains that human-generated pollution IS harmful to the environment, that's just a fact. In this movie, it was just used as a brief plot development device, nothing more. The story immediately moves on and doesn't address it outside of one speech a character gives, leaving nothing to get hung up about. I also appreciate the director's decision to sprinkle tidbits of Godzilla callbacks that will satiate fans on narrative elements they hadn't even considered going into the theater. It ties up the movie's atmosphere and lets the fans of this series know that the director cares about this project. The cherry on top is a beautiful soundtrack that brings more emotion into critical scenes of the film, driving it all home as a sublime cinematic Godzilla experience.   It's seriously depressing how brutal critics are with their reviews for this movie. I'm actually watching this trailer for the first time as I write this. I'm so happy I avoided trailers, and I got to see this film not knowing where the plot was landing next. This movie was awesome and I think it's worthy to be recognized in the Godzilla movie franchise as nothing short of a success. I've cared about this series since I was a kid, probably going for 15 years now, and it is just amazing seeing this franchise I love bring my favorite monsters to a gorgeous new movie. The flip side of that is it just kills me seeing the terrible reviews online, when half the critics are just comparing this to Endgame and the MCU. I hope this movie recovers from the brutal reviews, and I hope they continue the Monsterverse.

text: A poorly produced movie with a propaganda of hatred!  Walking out of the movie, I felt unsettled and I will probably not see another movie for the rest of the summer.  This is just another same-old story of human fighting "after-world" creatures, brought to viewers with dark & fuzzy scenes and low screen editing techniques.  I could not find the synchrony between the creatures' movement and the reaction of the actors on-screen.  They are just two independent worlds happening right in front of the audience; and of course, the audience would not be thrilled or scared by this backdrop creature movement.  These "sci-fi" animals, after scripting with underlying racism and hatred, are not harmful after all.  Save your money, give yourself some peace and choose to watch a different Hollywood hit at the theatre instead.

text: I had the answer on how to kill big monsters way back for Pacific Rim monsters (Kaiju).   You don't need a big mech costing Millions and tons of construction and pilots to drive them.   Here's the answer: You can use jet planes, really maneuverable and fast, with missiles that have the smallest nuclear warheads so we don't totally pollute the planet. The missiles just need to have really really hard/pokey tips. I mean REALLY POKEY and REALLY HARD so they can penetrate the monsters flesh/hide/scales/skin. Maybe made out of Carbon Steel or Tungsten Carbide. I'm sure there would be some scientists that could find something. Once it penetrates, it goes off. Sploosh and Done! Monster guts everywhere. It's hard to be a big ol' scary monster when you don't have any guts anymore, am I right?!?! Granted, you would need to pick your best attack time and approach and the jet would have to get in there, fire and get out. You would need some backup planes in case a monster swipes one or two out of the air. I'm thinking you have three at a time approach from 120 degrees apart so a least one would have an unseen approach by the monster.

text: Great film, very enjoyable. Critics are saying that they want more human drama, but frankly if they want human drama then they shouldn't be watching a monster movie. I personally thought that some of the human moments could've been cut, and that sometimes the on-the-ground humans got in the way of the real spectacle, but all-in-all, I was very satisfied with the experience.   [Spoilers]   There are two posters that I want. One of Mothra being beautiful, and one of the last shot of the film.   Godzilla stands towering over his cowering servants, as he gazes over his kingdom, a landscape of ash beneath a burning sky. Absolutely stunning.    Also Mothra and Godzilla have better chemistry than any human pair I've seen in years, I swear to god(zilla)

text: The reason this underperformed is that the trailers before this pushed Millie Bobby Brown too much without anticipating that there'd be overexposure of her to the market. Also, the whole core human storyline is exactly what you get in the trailers with humans being a virus that needs to be cleansed. Is this Philosophy 101 or a monster movie? Also, why do these disaster movies always have a lead actor who's divorced? I get that they wanted to parallel the family coming together with earth coming together, which is real cheesy, but couldn't you have just used humans from the previous movie and say they were divorced? You created a whole set of new characters whose defining traits are that they're in a broken family and that's it.

text: My review [Spoiler free]     The opening is perfect, very action packed and not boring and long, one of the best beginnings to a movie I have ever seen. I think they did an awesome job on all the titans, but especially mothra, its amazingly done how badass mothra is while at the same time to beautifull and peacefull. I think rodan has gotten the perfect design but could have used a little more screentime. King ghidorah is just perfect, like pure evil. I really like the look of him and his new abilaties. Godzilla, I dont have to say anything about him, its just perfect, the way he acts is awesome and I love the new spines and roar. The other titans where really cool too, I just hoped they actually did something. The family drama is well done too, I dont see how they put too little of it, first of all you are watching a movie about monsters, ofcourse it isnt gonna be fully about family drama, otherwise it will be like godzilla 2014, way too much family drama and too little monster fights, I think they nailed that part. The ending is also perfect 10/10

text: How This Trailer Really Fits the Monsterverse:  1.) The Music. The song Over the Rainbow expresses the beauty of this world, which is heavily emphasized in the trailers thus far. There is beauty in the most majestic figures, hence Mothra and Godzilla. Beauty can be found even in the destructive and terrifying aspects of reality, shown through Rodan and Ghidorah. The action in the last part of the trailer shows what we kaiju fans have been waiting for: fast-paced fighting with high levels of devastation.   2.) The Cinematography. Every shot of these kaiju represents what they are, something beyond mankind. Even if they are a superspecies/megafauna animal, their existence is to be in a higher realm of being. Especially with Ghidorah. He truly feels like he is a King, asserting himself over Godzilla with wings spread wide. For Godzilla, his power can be seen through his new and improved atomic breath and signature new roar. Even his sheer size can be felt in his shots with the sub and with Serizawa. This size of his makes Ghidorah even larger and scarier. Next is Rodan. His destruction in every shot from a bird's-eye and the normal view is breathtaking. His shots of being awakened are just stellar. Him slowly crawling out of that volcano with his slow movements makes for a very terrifying creature I hope to be impressed by in theaters. Last but not least, Mothra. The true beauty of this movie alongside Ghidorah in my opinion. Those shots of her spreading her wings, displaying the title of Queen of the Monsters...very good. I have no words to describe her shots in the trailers. The filmmakers did an AMAZING job with these kaiju overall.   3.) The Designs of the Kaiju: Every aspect of these kaiju just scream god. Everything from Ghidorah's size, Mothra's wings, and Godzilla himself. Just look at them in the trailers and they'll feel like mythological beasts that have entered our world and will be there forever.     NOT MINE  I'M JUST SHARING HE'S OPINION BECAUSE IT'S BREATHTAKING

text: Was so excited for this only for it to be so disappointing. Everyone complained the first didnt have enough monsters but for me because of that it really gave the monster scenes tremendous weight and mystery. I LOVED it. I got the chills the first godzilla sighting.  Each monster scene was holy fuck moments. This new movie that shock and awe is completely gone. The cuts are wayyyy to fast you never get a chance to really focus on the monsters before it cuts. And by god the script. It feels like it was just thrown together super quick and finished as the movie was shot. The story in my opinion feels like the writers just went with the first idea they had and ran with it without properly thinking and fleshing it out only to realize when it was to late. The motivations for veras character were just stupid and im actually shocked millie took this role after reading that script. Listen I know its a monster movie and they arent meant to be serious oscar contenders but im just so bummed. They should of stuck with gareth edwards at least he had a vision and there would of been some continuity as far as the monster sections go and he definitely was good at making the monster parts feel super epic and scary.  I basically feel exactly like I did after the pacific rim sequel. Like everything good about the 1st was just dumbed down or taken in a different direction completely.

text: Speaking only for myself,  having grown up watching the Showa, Heisei, and Millennium eras.  This is a franchise that literally has in its filmography *aliens, time traveling humans, intelligent apes, and sapient cockroaches trying to take over the planet, with allegories that are just as outlandish sometimes, and most (if not all) of these films feature characters whose acting range from hilariously bad to dull to just plain painful (and that was not always a dubbing issue either).*  That being said, I love those films with all of my heart!  Godzilla 1954, Ghidorah: The Three Headed Monster, most of the Heisei era, especially Godzilla vs Biollante!  Never the less, I can honestly say based on those past Godzilla films.  Godzilla: King of the Monster 2019 is just pure gold!  Well done Legendary Pictures!  Well done Michael Dougherty!  #LongLiveTheMonsterverse!

text: Phenomenal movie. Its one of the few movies that managed to raise my heartbeat. The combination of use of CGI, the audio (the monster screams omg), the music and the overall design of the monsters was amazing. It almost felt as if the story was too large to put into a 2 hour movie so they had to cut corners. You hardly get to see some of the other titans as a result. I also love how they're getting better at capturing the grand scale at which everything is happening, because in most movies it still feels like a CGI town being torn down, not a real one.   Still, as a point of improvement that I also notice in other movies is that they need to do some more research on how to mimic gravity when it comes to large scale monsters. When they fall it still feels like a rubber toy drops onto a fake building and casually cuts through them like butter. We're talking bricks, concrete, and harsh forces of nature here, like a meteor crushing the crust of the earth. As a human you don't just protect yourself from that from putting your arm in front of your face.   Otherwise, my vote for best movie of the year (and yes that includes Avengers Endgame).

text: I realized how bad this movie sucked 9 minutes, 31 seconds in. Why was her only surviving child allowed to roam freely in a top secret, government facility that was housing some goddamn monster they knew virtually nothing about? I didn't see anyone elses kids in there. One child was already dead because of these things, so her brilliant idea was to bring her last child alive, into this place to watch this thing be born? Really?   I'm at 24 minutes, 6 seconds now and according to the movie thus far, women are the vastly superior people, *_AT EVERYTHING_*  (big leftist, SJW surprise, I know).   Women lead the science program. Women head the government inquiry. Women pilot the plane/copter. Women lead the military unit to go after the big fucking caterpillar thing.  Lest we forget, the token, beta boy, cuck lawyer, complete with the shitty looking, soy boy beard, being portrayed as nothing more than a whiny little weak bitch who gets shut down by everyone around him.  Why did only one man on the containment team, fire at the caterpillar when it showed aggression? They all had their weapons trained on it, yet the moment something went wrong, nobody else fired. What?  Ol drunk boy, loser, dad "helped" build the prototype orca thing, destroyed it, then she rebuilt the thing all by herself, implying that;  A. She is intellectually, electronically, and mechanically superior to him, and....  B. He was unnecessary to the process to begin with.  Tywin Lannister was ruthless enough to kill all the scientists, who were 99% male, (I only saw one other woman in the room), but her and her kid, who just happened to be there, inside a top secret government facility, (did I mention that?) but had the foresight and generosity of spirit to have winter coats, that fit perfectly btw, for them both to wear so they wouldn't get the sniffles. I gotta say, that was mighty white of him to do that for them.  I'm only 24 minutes in, and it already sucks my ass. Hollywood is for nothing but shit today. No such thing as entertainment anymore. *_FAIL!_*

text: Kudos to Warner Bros. for making this, the best/worst allegory of the 2016 elections we are likely to ever come across. And away we go.  First, some well meaning, but ultimately clueless bunch of people unleash one guy on an unsuspecting world. A guy, who wants to recreate the world to suit himself. Second, another bunch of equally well meaning, but equally clueless people end up taking out the wrong guy. (This poor victim, to his credit, has slightly more scruples than the other one.) They take him out with a 'green' bomb no less. (Pun intended!). Three, that leaves the rest of the people scurrying about in the sheer horror of the situation. Four, everyone waits with bated breath for the climax, that finally comes. (In the movie, anyway.) Cue, next disaster (rous) movie sequel.   And finally, towards the end of the movie there is that gem of a  badinage that alluded to most of the politicians:   Character A: Jesus! Good thing he's on our side! Character B : For Now!   It is one disaster even Mr. Watanabe Ken can't save us from. (Again, pun intended.)    The monster fights were awesome though.  You keep makin' em'. We will keep watchin' em'.

text: March 7, 2020       What is up Godzilla fans how are you doing today, if you have not seen Godzilla King of The Monsters consider this your spoiler warning. Now the Visual Effects are stunning from the birth of Mothra and the resurrection of Godzilla. The music composed by Bear McCreary is incredible that directly links with the spiritual themes of the story specifically King Ghidorah's declaration as the new Alpha of the Titans with the cross silhouetted in shadow and fire. The villains Alan Jonah and King Ghidorah are mirror reflections of each other, Alan wanted to fix humanity whose ravaging Earth and Ghidorah wanted to rebuild the planet in his image; the Kajiu action scenes are amazing for example Godzilla and King Ghidorah's faceoff in the Arctic. My only criticism, the pacing was a little slow overall I give King Of The Monsters 9.1 stars out of ten I'm Daniel Oleszek and I approve this review have a great day.

text: I have NEVER BEEN more excited to see a movie in Theaters until this came out. When I first saw it not only was I excited but I was even more happy after the movie ended. I loved Godzilla King of the Monsters. So much nostalgia in one movie. I mean my god Godzillaâ€™s roar is fantastic like always, Mothra looked so beautiful and terrifying at the same time, Rodan while underused was still great and had a good design...BUT...King Ghidorah my god they did such a good job on him I was shaking in my seat. They remixed his OG ROAR, remixed his OG Theme and heâ€™s fucking huge and terrifying. He looks so fucking bad ass. And they made him super violent which I really liked I wanted previous Godzilla movies to do that but luckily I got my wish with this movie. And the fact that his middle head got a name and was a center point to the fight made me smile. In Destroy All Monsters King Ghidorahâ€™s middle head was damaged the most and was the first part of his body to die & in Godzilla Vs King Ghidorah his middle head gets blown off just like in this movie!!! And they kinda hinted and making maybe a Mecha King Ghidorah in the future HOPEFULLY! On top of all of that thereâ€™s just so many other Easter eggs in this movie i canâ€™t name them all but Iâ€™m just very happy that Godzilla King of the Monsters did pretty good with critics and did well with fans but honestly they donâ€™t matter, as long as I enjoyed the movie and I did. I really hope Godzilla Vs Kong does well too. A remake for King Kong Vs Godzilla was something I dreamed of when I was a kid and I canâ€™t believe my wish is coming true.
